article.description: Renee Montgomery scored all of her 20 points in the first half to lead top-ranked Connecticut to a 78-41 win over in-state rival Hartford on Wednesday.
article.headline: Montgomery scores 20 as UConn rolls
article.linkText: No. 1 UConn routs Hartford behind Montgomery
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. -- An elbow to the mouth was the only thing that stopped Connecticut's Renee Montgomery on Wednesday.

The senior point guard scored all of her 20 points in the first half to lead the top-ranked Huskies to a 78-41 win over in-state rival Hartford.

Montgomery missed most of the second half after an elbow from Illicia Mathis split her lower lip and loosened a tooth while she battled under the basket on defense. She returned to the bench but did not play the remainder of the game.

Montgomery, who hit nine of her 11 shots, moved past Hartford coach Jen Rizzotti into 12th place on UConn's all-time scoring list with 1,545 points.

"How appropriate," Rizzotti said. "She just is a machine right now. She is playing phenomenal basketball, as good as anyone in the country and she has so much confidence that every shot she shoots is going to go in. She runs the team really well, so she is doing a lot for the basketball team."

Tina Charles scored 17 points and pulled down nine rebounds for UConn, which improved to 12-0. The Huskies, coming off a five-game road trip, won their 30th consecutive home game.

Mathis had 10 points to lead Hartford (5-7), which upset No. 6 Duke 53-51 in November, but was never really in this one.

Connecticut missed its first five shots, and led only 6-2 early in the game. But the Hawks went nearly five minutes without a field goal and the Huskies moved ahead 14-2 with 13:40 left when Montgomery hit a 3-pointer.

"I got some open shots," Montgomery said. "Sometimes they go in, and sometimes they don't, but I had some open shots, which is because of [my teammates] for screening."

Hartford had just six field goals in the first half and trailed 49-16 at halftime.

Maya Moore, who had been averaging nearly 19 points, incurred coach Geno Auriemma's wrath after a defensive lapse in the first half. She played only 18 minutes, scoring a season-low 11 points.

"I don't know that if you're the best player in the country, that you should just get out of the way and let people shoot layups," Auriemma said. "That's probably not the winning edge."

Moore said she got the message.

"I'm not going to be upset with him," she said. "I'm just going to do what I can to fix it and improve my game."

The Huskies are 12-0 for the third straight season and the 10th time in the last 13 years.

UConn won its 98th straight game against an unranked opponent. The Huskies are 24-0 against in-state opponents since Auriemma became coach in 1985.

The Huskies host LSU in a nationally televised game on Saturday, and Auriemma said he's sure Montgomery will be ready to go.

"She didn't grab her knee. She didn't grab her ankle," Auriemma said. "Once I saw it was her mouth, I lost interest."
